Crude Oil Volatility Drops as Futures Fall 16 Cents This Week

-- B y   M a r g o t   H a b i b y
-- 
2011-05-20T21:15:33Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-20/crude-oil-volatility-drops-as-futures-fall-16-cents-this-week.html
Oil options fell as June futures
slipped 16 cents this week on the  New York Mercantile Exchange .  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
July, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a gauge
of options prices, was 33.3 percent as of 4 p.m. in  New York ,
down from 33.8 percent yesterday.  Crude for June delivery rose $1.05, or 1.1 percent, to
settle at $99.49 a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
Prices have climbed 46 percent in the past year. June futures
expired at the close of floor trading. The more-active July
contract gained $1.17, or 1.2 percent, to $100.10 a barrel.  The most active contracts in electronic trading today were
July $85 puts, with 3,759 lots changing hands. They lost 3 cents
to 37 cents a barrel. July $90 puts, the next-most active
option, retreated 16 cents to 76 cents a barrel with 3,080 lots
trading. One contract covers 1,000 barrels of crude.  June options expired May 17 on the exchange.  Nymex distributes real-time data for electronic trading and
releases information on floor trading, where the bulk of options
trading occurs, the next business day.  July $128 calls were the most active options traded
yesterday, with 10,813 lots changing hands. They slipped 6 cents
to 10 cents a barrel. The next-most active options, December
2012 $140 calls, lost 18 cents to $2.83 a barrel on volume of
6,382 lots.  Open interest was highest for December 2012 $80 puts with
46,226 contracts. Next were December 2011 $120 calls with 39,690
and December 2011 $100 calls with 37,294.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Margot Habiby in  Dallas  at 
 mhabiby@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Bill Banker at 
 bbanker@bloomberg.net . 